The article is about a joint message on climate change negotiations between the United States and Japan. The leaders of both countries affirm their commitment to working together to fight climate change and recognize each other's achievements in this area. They emphasize the importance of transitioning to low-carbon growth for the health of the planet and the global economy. The countries aspire to reduce their own emissions by 80% by 2050 and endorse a global goal of reducing emissions by 50% by that year. They emphasize the need for ambitious actions by all major economies, including emission reduction targets by developed countries and significant emission reductions by major developing countries. They also stress the importance of reporting and international review of these actions. Additionally, they highlight the need for support for climate mitigation and adaptation efforts among the poor and most vulnerable. The United States and Japan will continue to cooperate closely in international negotiations and are determined to achieve a successful outcome at COP 15.